  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Apollodorus, of Athens Scholar, 2nd cent. BC, His Χρονικά (Chroniká) 
    in four books lists historical events in chronological order. Its composition in iambic trimeters was intended a
    s a mnemonic aid. The first three books extend to 144/3, and the fourth concludes the series. It was based on the Χρονογραφίαι 
    (Chronographíai) of Eratosthenes, which it replaced in public estimation and in its coverage. Eratosthenes had stopped at the death of Alexander the Great in 323
    A. continues the chronicle until shortly before his own death in about 110 BC, like Eratosthenes dating the fall of Troy to 1184/3, 
    but following Ephorus in putting Homer's composition much later, in 944/3....." from Montanari, Franco (Pisa). "Apollodorus."
    Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and
    Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2011. Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 05 October 2011</mads:note>
